  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Python Reference for Time Series and Sequence Learning\n",
        "\n",
        "This appendix collects the Python patterns used throughout the book.  It is designed as a practical companion for the labs.  The goal is not to replace documentation for `numpy`, `pandas`, `statsmodels`, `scikit-learn`, `torch`, or `plotly`, but to give students a consistent workflow for simulation, visualization, modeling, validation, and debugging.\n",
        "\n",
        "The guiding principle is simple: in time series, code must respect time order.  Random shuffling, scaling with future data, or using future observations as features can make a model look much better than it really is.\n",
        "\n",
        "## A.1 Recommended Python environment\n",
        "\n",
        "The labs are written for Python 3.10 or later.  A standard environment should include the following packages."
      ],
      "id": "13d72e19"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "# Core scientific stack\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Time series tools\n",
        "from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf\n",
        "from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import acf, pacf, adfuller\n",
        "from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA\n",
        "from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX\n",
        "from statsmodels.stats.diagnostic import acorr_ljungbox\n",
        "\n",
        "# Machine learning tools\n",
        "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression, Ridge\n",
        "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor, GradientBoostingRegressor\n",
        "from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "\n",
        "# Optional deep learning tools\n",
        "import torch\n",
        "import torch.nn as nn\n",
        "from torch.utils.data import Dataset, DataLoader"
      ],
      "id": "071ebf5e",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
