    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 3))\n",
        "plot_acf(y.dropna(), lags=30, ax=ax)\n",
        "ax.set_title(\"Sample ACF\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 3))\n",
        "plot_pacf(y.dropna(), lags=30, ax=ax, method=\"ywm\")\n",
        "ax.set_title(\"Sample PACF\")\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "1367948d",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.5 Common simulation patterns\n",
        "\n",
        "### White noise\n",
        "\n",
        "White noise has mean zero, constant variance, and zero autocovariance at nonzero lags."
      ],
      "id": "d1042129"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "n = 400\n",
        "sigma = 1.0\n",
        "w = rng.normal(0, sigma, size=n)"
      ],
      "id": "0d3ab7a5",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Random walk\n",
        "\n",
        "The random walk satisfies $X_t = X_{t-1} + W_t$."
      ],
      "id": "715e6e00"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "x_rw = np.cumsum(w)"
      ],
      "id": "e075eb6d",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### AR(1)\n",
        "\n",
        "The AR(1) model is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t = \\phi X_{t-1} + W_t.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "747eba87"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "n = 400\n",
        "burnin = 200\n",
        "total = n + burnin\n",
        "phi = 0.75\n",
        "w = rng.normal(0, 1, size=total)\n",
        "x_full = np.zeros(total)\n",
        "\n",
        "for t in range(1, total):\n",
        "    x_full[t] = phi * x_full[t - 1] + w[t]\n",
        "\n",
        "x_ar1 = x_full[burnin:]\n",
        "assert len(x_ar1) == n"
      ],
      "id": "6c960ec8",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### MA(1)\n",
        "\n",
        "The MA(1) model is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t = W_t + \\theta W_{t-1}.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "a85f2176"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "theta = 0.70\n",
        "x_full = np.zeros(total)\n",
        "\n",
        "for t in range(1, total):\n",
        "    x_full[t] = w[t] + theta * w[t - 1]\n",
        "\n",
        "x_ma1 = x_full[burnin:]\n",
        "assert len(x_ma1) == n"
      ],
      "id": "7928f3d5",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### ARMA(1,1)\n",
        "\n",
        "The ARMA(1,1) model is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t = \\phi X_{t-1} + W_t + \\theta W_{t-1}.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "bd1a9b2f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "phi = 0.65\n",
        "theta = 0.50\n",
        "x_full = np.zeros(total)\n",
        "\n",
        "for t in range(1, total):\n",
        "    x_full[t] = phi * x_full[t - 1] + w[t] + theta * w[t - 1]\n",
        "\n",
        "x_arma11 = x_full[burnin:]\n",
        "assert len(x_arma11) == n"
      ],
      "id": "0431699d",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.6 Sample autocovariance and ACF from scratch\n",
        "\n",
        "The sample autocovariance at lag $h$ is often estimated by\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat{\\gamma}(h)\n",
        "= \\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{t=h+1}^{n} (x_t-\\bar{x})(x_{t-h}-\\bar{x}).\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "b874f2b1"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def sample_autocovariance(x, max_lag):\n",
        "    x = np.asarray(x, dtype=float)\n",
        "    n = len(x)\n",
        "    x_centered = x - x.mean()\n",
        "    gamma = []\n",
        "    for h in range(max_lag + 1):\n",
        "        value = np.sum(x_centered[h:] * x_centered[:n - h]) / n\n",
        "        gamma.append(value)\n",
        "    return np.array(gamma)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def sample_acf(x, max_lag):\n",
        "    gamma = sample_autocovariance(x, max_lag)\n",
        "    return gamma / gamma[0]\n",
        "\n",
        "rho_hat = sample_acf(x_ar1, max_lag=20)"
      ],
      "id": "39335e83",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.7 Train, validation, and test splits\n",
        "\n",
        "For forecasting, split by time order."
      ],
      "id": "93ab6fe8"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def chronological_split(y, train_frac=0.7, val_frac=0.15):\n",
        "    n = len(y)\n",
        "    n_train = int(train_frac * n)\n",
        "    n_val = int(val_frac * n)\n",
        "\n",
        "    train = y.iloc[:n_train]\n",
        "    val = y.iloc[n_train:n_train + n_val]\n",
        "    test = y.iloc[n_train + n_val:]\n",
        "\n",
        "    return train, val, test\n",
        "\n",
        "train, val, test = chronological_split(y)"
      ],
      "id": "b40cbffd",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Avoid this for forecasting:"
      ],
      "id": "7f0c76f6"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "# Do not use this for time-series forecasting validation.\n",
        "# from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
        "# train, test = train_test_split(y, test_size=0.2, shuffle=True)"
      ],
      "id": "e4915bb6",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.8 Forecasting metrics\n",
        "\n",
        "For observations $y_t$ and forecasts $\\widehat{y}_t$, common point-forecast metrics include\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{MAE} = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{t=1}^{n}|y_t-\\widehat{y}_t|,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{RMSE} = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{t=1}^{n}(y_t-\\widehat{y}_t)^2}.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "a8ba1b2e"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def rmse(y_true, y_pred):\n",
        "    y_true = np.asarray(y_true)\n",
        "    y_pred = np.asarray(y_pred)\n",
        "    return np.sqrt(np.mean((y_true - y_pred) ** 2))\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def mae(y_true, y_pred):\n",
        "    y_true = np.asarray(y_true)\n",
        "    y_pred = np.asarray(y_pred)\n",
        "    return np.mean(np.abs(y_true - y_pred))"
      ],
      "id": "f62a8960",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "For seasonal data, a seasonal naive model is an essential baseline."
      ],
      "id": "abffaef3"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def seasonal_naive_forecast(y_train, horizon, season_length):\n",
        "    y_train = np.asarray(y_train)\n",
        "    if len(y_train) < season_length:\n",
        "        raise ValueError(\"Training series must be at least one seasonal period long.\")\n",
        "    repeats = int(np.ceil(horizon / season_length))\n",
        "    forecast = np.tile(y_train[-season_length:], repeats)[:horizon]\n",
        "    return forecast"
      ],
      "id": "bcc0b597",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.9 Rolling-origin backtesting\n",
        "\n",
        "Rolling-origin evaluation repeatedly refits or updates the model using only past data."
      ],
      "id": "2931c25f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def rolling_origin_splits(n, initial_window, horizon, step=1):\n",
        "    starts = []\n",
        "    train_ends = []\n",
        "    test_ranges = []\n",
        "\n",
        "    train_end = initial_window\n",
        "    while train_end + horizon <= n:\n",
        "        starts.append(0)\n",
        "        train_ends.append(train_end)\n",
        "        test_ranges.append((train_end, train_end + horizon))\n",
        "        train_end += step\n",
        "\n",
        "    return list(zip(starts, train_ends, test_ranges))\n",
        "\n",
        "splits = rolling_origin_splits(n=200, initial_window=100, horizon=12, step=12)"
      ],
      "id": "4ddfd08b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "A template for evaluating a simple forecasting function is:"
      ],
      "id": "ecdb923a"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def evaluate_rolling_origin(y, forecast_function, initial_window, horizon, step=1):\n",
        "    y = pd.Series(y).reset_index(drop=True)\n",
        "    records = []\n",
        "\n",
        "    for start, train_end, (test_start, test_end) in rolling_origin_splits(\n",
        "        len(y), initial_window, horizon, step\n",
        "    ):\n",
        "        y_train = y.iloc[start:train_end]\n",
        "        y_test = y.iloc[test_start:test_end]\n",
        "        y_pred = forecast_function(y_train, horizon)\n",
        "\n",
        "        records.append({\n",
        "            \"train_end\": train_end,\n",
        "            \"horizon\": horizon,\n",
        "            \"mae\": mae(y_test, y_pred),\n",
        "            \"rmse\": rmse(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "        })\n",
        "\n",
        "    return pd.DataFrame(records)"
      ],
      "id": "1419a7bc",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.10 Fitting ARIMA and SARIMA models\n",
        "\n",
        "A basic ARIMA fit uses `statsmodels`."
      ],
      "id": "407bbc44"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "model = ARIMA(train, order=(1, 1, 1))\n",
        "result = model.fit()\n",
        "print(result.summary())\n",
        "\n",
        "forecast_result = result.get_forecast(steps=len(test))\n",
        "forecast_mean = forecast_result.predicted_mean\n",
        "forecast_interval = forecast_result.conf_int()"
      ],
      "id": "f89d832f",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "A SARIMA model can be fitted with `SARIMAX`."
      ],
      "id": "f5abb8ff"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "model = SARIMAX(\n",
        "    train,\n",
        "    order=(1, 1, 1),\n",
        "    seasonal_order=(1, 1, 1, 12),\n",
        "    enforce_stationarity=False,\n",
        "    enforce_invertibility=False\n",
        ")\n",
        "result = model.fit(disp=False)\n",
        "forecast = result.get_forecast(steps=len(test))"
      ],
      "id": "59c53575",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Residual diagnostics should always be checked."
      ],
      "id": "aeb3df9a"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "resid = result.resid.dropna()\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 3))\n",
        "plot_acf(resid, lags=30, ax=ax)\n",
        "ax.set_title(\"Residual ACF\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "lb = acorr_ljungbox(resid, lags=[10, 20], return_df=True)\n",
        "lb"
      ],
      "id": "da3b0854",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.11 Supervised learning matrix from lags\n",
        "\n",
        "Many machine learning models require turning a time series into a supervised learning table."
      ],
      "id": "0a0a461b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def make_lagged_frame(y, lags, horizon=1):\n",
        "    y = pd.Series(y).reset_index(drop=True)\n",
        "    data = pd.DataFrame({\"y\": y})\n",
        "\n",
        "    for lag in lags:\n",
        "        data[f\"lag_{lag}\"] = data[\"y\"].shift(lag)\n",
        "\n",
        "    data[\"target\"] = data[\"y\"].shift(-horizon)\n",
        "    data = data.dropna().reset_index(drop=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "    X = data[[f\"lag_{lag}\" for lag in lags]]\n",
        "    target = data[\"target\"]\n",
        "    return X, target\n",
        "\n",
        "X_lag, y_target = make_lagged_frame(y, lags=[1, 2, 3, 7], horizon=1)"
      ],
      "id": "426cb961",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The scaling rule is important.  Fit scalers only on training data."
      ],
      "id": "54cb6093"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "split = int(0.8 * len(X_lag))\n",
        "X_train, X_test = X_lag.iloc[:split], X_lag.iloc[split:]\n",
        "y_train, y_test = y_target.iloc[:split], y_target.iloc[split:]\n",
        "\n",
        "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
        "X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)\n",
        "X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "model = Ridge(alpha=1.0)\n",
        "model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)\n",
        "y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"MAE:\", mae(y_test, y_pred))\n",
        "print(\"RMSE:\", rmse(y_test, y_pred))"
      ],
      "id": "85ef0a63",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.12 Window datasets for neural networks\n",
        "\n",
        "For neural networks, a common supervised learning format is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "(x_{t-L+1},\\ldots,x_t) \\mapsto (x_{t+1},\\ldots,x_{t+H}).\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "8fc4a7fe"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def make_windows(y, input_length, horizon):\n",
        "    y = np.asarray(y, dtype=np.float32)\n",
        "    X = []\n",
        "    Y = []\n",
        "    for start in range(0, len(y) - input_length - horizon + 1):\n",
        "        end = start + input_length\n",
        "        X.append(y[start:end])\n",
        "        Y.append(y[end:end + horizon])\n",
        "    return np.array(X), np.array(Y)\n",
        "\n",
        "X_win, Y_win = make_windows(y.values, input_length=24, horizon=12)\n",
        "print(X_win.shape, Y_win.shape)"
      ],
      "id": "899d2970",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "A minimal PyTorch dataset is:"
      ],
      "id": "2d267f12"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "class WindowDataset(Dataset):\n",
        "    def __init__(self, X, Y):\n",
        "        self.X = torch.tensor(X, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
        "        self.Y = torch.tensor(Y, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __len__(self):\n",
        "        return len(self.X)\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __getitem__(self, idx):\n",
        "        return self.X[idx], self.Y[idx]\n",
        "\n",
        "train_ds = WindowDataset(X_win, Y_win)\n",
        "train_loader = DataLoader(train_ds, batch_size=32, shuffle=False)"
      ],
      "id": "7f8b8c2a",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "For forecasting, avoid shuffling validation and test windows.  Shuffling training windows is sometimes acceptable for neural-network optimization after the windows have been created without leakage, but validation must remain chronological.\n",
        "\n",
        "## A.13 Minimal neural network forecaster"
      ],
      "id": "074cee69"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "class MLPForecaster(nn.Module):\n",
        "    def __init__(self, input_length, horizon, hidden=64):\n",
        "        super().__init__()\n",
        "        self.net = nn.Sequential(\n",
        "            nn.Linear(input_length, hidden),\n",
        "            nn.ReLU(),\n",
        "            nn.Linear(hidden, hidden),\n",
        "            nn.ReLU(),\n",
        "            nn.Linear(hidden, horizon)\n",
        "        )\n",
        "\n",
        "    def forward(self, x):\n",
        "        return self.net(x)\n",
        "\n",
        "model = MLPForecaster(input_length=24, horizon=12)\n",
        "optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=1e-3)\n",
        "loss_fn = nn.MSELoss()"
      ],
      "id": "b18ccfc8",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "A small training loop:"
      ],
      "id": "2bc53669"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "for epoch in range(20):\n",
        "    model.train()\n",
        "    total_loss = 0.0\n",
        "\n",
        "    for xb, yb in train_loader:\n",
        "        optimizer.zero_grad()\n",
        "        pred = model(xb)\n",
        "        loss = loss_fn(pred, yb)\n",
        "        loss.backward()\n",
        "        optimizer.step()\n",
        "        total_loss += loss.item() * len(xb)\n",
        "\n",
        "    avg_loss = total_loss / len(train_loader.dataset)\n",
        "    print(f\"epoch={epoch + 1:02d}, train_mse={avg_loss:.4f}\")"
      ],
      "id": "61707987",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.14 Causal convolution helper\n",
        "\n",
        "A 1D causal convolution should not use future values.  The output at time $t$ may depend on $x_t,x_{t-1},x_{t-2},\\ldots$, but not on $x_{t+1}$."
      ],
      "id": "0725b1fc"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def causal_convolution_1d(x, kernel, dilation=1):\n",
        "    x = np.asarray(x, dtype=float)\n",
        "    kernel = np.asarray(kernel, dtype=float)\n",
        "    n = len(x)\n",
        "    k = len(kernel)\n",
        "    y = np.zeros(n)\n",
        "\n",
        "    for t in range(n):\n",
        "        value = 0.0\n",
        "        for j in range(k):\n",
        "            idx = t - dilation * j\n",
        "            if idx >= 0:\n",
        "                value += kernel[j] * x[idx]\n",
        "        y[t] = value\n",
        "\n",
        "    return y"
      ],
      "id": "c356cdad",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The receptive field of a stack of dilated convolutions with kernel size $K$ and dilations $d_1,\\ldots,d_L$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "R = 1 + (K-1)\\sum_{\\ell=1}^{L} d_\\ell.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "## A.15 Attention helper functions\n",
        "\n",
        "The scaled dot-product attention formula is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{Attention}(Q,K,V)\n",
        "= \\operatorname{softmax}\\left(\\frac{QK^T}{\\sqrt{d_k}} + M\\right)V.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "4b5a3bf5"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "def softmax_rows(A):\n",
        "    A = A - A.max(axis=1, keepdims=True)\n",
        "    E = np.exp(A)\n",
        "    return E / E.sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def scaled_dot_product_attention(Q, K, V, mask=None):\n",
        "    d_k = Q.shape[-1]\n",
        "    scores = Q @ K.T / np.sqrt(d_k)\n",
        "    if mask is not None:\n",
        "        scores = scores + mask\n",
        "    weights = softmax_rows(scores)\n",
        "    output = weights @ V\n",
        "    return output, weights\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def causal_mask(T):\n",
        "    M = np.triu(np.ones((T, T)), k=1)\n",
        "    return np.where(M == 1, -1e9, 0.0)"
      ],
      "id": "f86e6e22",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.16 Plotly interactive pattern for this book\n",
        "\n",
        "Plotly.js is included once globally in `assets/header.html`.  Interactive modules should use the shared configuration in `assets/ts-interactives.js`.\n",
        "\n",
        "A standard pattern is:\n",
        "\n",
        "```{js}\n",
        "//| eval: false\n",
        "window.TSInteractives = window.TSInteractives || {};\n",
        "\n",
        "window.TSInteractives.exampleModule = function () {\n",
        "  const plotDiv = document.getElementById(\"example-plot\");\n",
        "  if (!plotDiv || typeof Plotly === \"undefined\") return;\n",
        "\n",
        "  const traces = [\n",
        "    { x: [0, 1, 2], y: [0, 1, 0], mode: \"lines\", name: \"example\" }\n",
        "  ];\n",
        "\n",
        "  const layout = {\n",
        "    title: \"Example Interactive\",\n",
        "    margin: { t: 60, r: 30, b: 50, l: 50 }\n",
        "  };\n",
        "\n",
        "  Plotly.react(\n",
        "    plotDiv,\n",
        "    traces,\n",
        "    layout,\n",
        "    window.TSInteractives.plotlyConfig\n",
        "  );\n",
        "};\n",
        "\n",
        "document.addEventListener(\"DOMContentLoaded\", function () {\n",
        "  window.TSInteractives.exampleModule();\n",
        "});\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "The chapter `.qmd` file should contain only the container, not another Plotly script tag.\n",
        "\n",
        "```{markdown}\n",
        "```html\n",
        "<div class=\"interactive-card\">\n",
        "  <h3>Interactive Module</h3>\n",
        "  <div id=\"example-plot\" style=\"width:100%; height:480px;\"></div>\n",
        "</div>\n",
        "```\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "## A.17 Common debugging checklist\n",
        "\n",
        "When a lab or interactive does not work, check these items first.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Confirm the notebook runtime is using Python 3.10 or later.\n",
        "- Run all cells from the top instead of running isolated cells out of order.\n",
        "- Check array lengths after differencing, lagging, and windowing.\n",
        "- Use `assert` statements for expected shapes.\n",
        "- Make sure scaling is fitted only on the training set.\n",
        "- Make sure validation and test sets are later in time than the training set.\n",
        "- Check that `assets/header.html` loads Plotly.js once.\n",
        "- Check browser developer tools for missing file errors such as `404 Not Found`.\n",
        "- Check that each interactive container ID matches the JavaScript code.\n",
        "- Avoid raw HTML tables inside Quarto documents when rendering to PDF.\n",
        "\n",
        "Useful shape checks:"
      ],
      "id": "d6218fed"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "assert len(y_train) > 0\n",
        "assert len(y_test) > 0\n",
        "assert X_train.shape[0] == len(y_train)\n",
        "assert X_test.shape[0] == len(y_test)\n",
        "assert np.isfinite(X_train).all().all()\n",
        "assert np.isfinite(y_train).all()"
      ],
      "id": "f42d9dc6",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.18 AI-assisted Python workflow\n",
        "\n",
        "AI tools are helpful for code review, but they must be asked precise, time-series-aware questions.  Good prompts include the data structure, the forecast horizon, the information set, and the validation design.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example prompt:\n",
        "\n",
        "> I am forecasting $y_{t+12}$ using only information available up to time $t$.  Here is my feature construction and train/test split.  Check whether any feature leaks future information.  Also check whether my scaling is fitted only on the training set.\n",
        "\n",
        "Another useful prompt:\n",
        "\n",
        "> Here is my residual ACF, Ljung-Box result, and rolling-origin error table.  Give three possible reasons the model fails, and propose checks that I can verify with code.\n",
        "\n",
        "AI-generated code should be treated as a draft.  Before using it in a project, verify the following.\n",
        "\n",
        "- The model does not use future observations as predictors.\n",
        "- Differencing, scaling, and feature engineering are performed in the correct chronological order.\n",
        "- The validation method matches the forecasting task.\n",
        "- Baselines are included.\n",
        "- Residual diagnostics are checked.\n",
        "- The code is reproducible from a fresh runtime.\n",
        "\n",
        "## A.19 Minimal project notebook structure\n",
        "\n",
        "A strong final-project notebook should follow this structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Problem statement and forecast contract.\n",
        "2. Data loading and cleaning.\n",
        "3. Exploratory time-series analysis.\n",
        "4. Baseline models.\n",
        "5. Main models.\n",
        "6. Rolling-origin or chronological validation.\n",
        "7. Residual diagnostics and uncertainty.\n",
        "8. Interpretation and limitations.\n",
        "9. Final conclusion.\n",
        "\n",
        "A simple project header can be:"
      ],
      "id": "4d4da2e6"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "PROJECT_TITLE = \"Short descriptive title\"\n",
        "FORECAST_TARGET = \"variable to forecast\"\n",
        "FORECAST_HORIZON = 12\n",
        "INFORMATION_SET = \"all variables observed up to forecast origin t\"\n",
        "VALIDATION_SCHEME = \"rolling-origin evaluation\"\n",
        "RANDOM_SEED = 7339"
      ],
      "id": "342b2865",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## A.20 Key principle\n",
        "\n",
        "For sequence data, the order is part of the data.  A model that ignores the order may still be useful, but a validation procedure that ignores the order is usually misleading."
      ],
      "id": "605c3a6f"
    }
  ],
